The article discusses how the federal minimum wage in the United States is being increased to $15 per hour for federal workers and employees of federal contractors. This increase will benefit nearly 70,000 federal workers and 300,000 contractors over the course of the year. The article emphasizes that this pay increase will provide workers, particularly women, workers of color, and workers with disabilities, with more financial stability. Additionally, it suggests that higher wages lead to increased productivity and reduced job turnover. The article concludes by urging Congress to raise the federal minimum wage to $15 per hour to ensure that all American workers can have jobs that provide dignity.